But with that I'm gonna turn it over to Joe

6
00:00:17.490 --> 00:00:20.583
as we take a look at some pediatric orthopedic issues.

7
00:00:23.010 --> 00:00:23.843
<v ->Great.</v>

8
00:00:23.843 --> 00:00:26.490
So as we look at pediatric orthopedic issues,

9
00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:30.983
we're gonna talk about some of the more common

10
00:00:32.580 --> 00:00:36.360
in the pediatric orthopedic world.

11
00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:40.080
A lots of most common, okay.

12
00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:43.140
They might not be common in our world,

13
00:00:43.140 --> 00:00:44.880
they're common in their world

14
00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:46.680
and we need to know about them.

15
00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:51.680
We're gonna talk about intoeing the apophysitis

16
00:00:51.990 --> 00:00:54.240
and then we're gonna talk a little bit

17
00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:57.540
about complications of obesity.

18
00:00:57.540 --> 00:00:59.070
I wanna bring this to your attention.

19
00:00:59.070 --> 00:01:03.000
This is PGALS, pediatric gait, arm, leg, and spine.

20
00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.950
And it's really a great screening test or tool.

21
00:01:07.950 --> 00:01:11.250
This is not gonna be on the exam. I haven't seen it.

22
00:01:11.250 --> 00:01:16.250
It's not old, but it's been around for 15 plus years.

23
00:01:17.236 --> 00:01:21.930
But it is really a great tool to utilize.

24
00:01:21.930 --> 00:01:24.870
You can Google it, take a look at the video.

25
00:01:24.870 --> 00:01:28.170
It literally takes about two minutes to do your screening,

26
00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:30.630
musculoskeletal exam with it.

27
00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:35.630
And then Dr. Foster has developed submodules.

28
00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:38.699
So you know, if my knee exam is abnormal,

29
00:01:38.699 --> 00:01:42.240
then I have a submodule that I can do for my knee.

30
00:01:42.240 --> 00:01:45.720
If my shoulder exam or my spine exam is abnormal,

31
00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:47.490
I've got these submodules.

32
00:01:47.490 --> 00:01:51.300
So it's really very helpful to use and utilize.

33
00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:55.470
And once you use it three or four times in your practice,

34
00:01:55.470 --> 00:01:59.853
you'll get it and it will all be pretty automatic.

35
00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:04.170
We're gonna start by talking about

36
00:02:04.170 --> 00:02:05.730
Duchenne's muscular dystrophy,

37
00:02:05.730 --> 00:02:08.040
because this is the most common fatal disease

38
00:02:08.040 --> 00:02:09.333
affecting children.

39
00:02:10.470 --> 00:02:13.273
Typically males who are affected.

40
00:02:13.273 --> 00:02:17.910
Onset is usually around that five to six year age range

41
00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:21.120
when they start becoming a little bit more clumsy.

42
00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:23.520
They may fall a little bit more.

43
00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:28.520
They develop that calf pseudo hypertrophy that can occur.

44
00:02:30.030 --> 00:02:32.760
And it takes a while to make this diagnosis

45
00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:33.930
because it's not something

46
00:02:33.930 --> 00:02:37.710
that we oftentimes think about upfront.

47
00:02:37.710 --> 00:02:41.195
A lot of times, we just reassure them,

48
00:02:41.195 --> 00:02:44.190
well, you know, Johnny or Susie or whatever

49
00:02:44.190 --> 00:02:47.610
may be a little clumsy, and that may be it,

50
00:02:47.610 --> 00:02:51.270
you know, let's see how it plays out over time.

51
00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:53.340
You know, it could be three or four months later

52
00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:54.840
when they come in,

53
00:02:54.840 --> 00:02:57.120
they basically look normal on their exam,

54
00:02:57.120 --> 00:03:00.690
particularly if we don't get them completely undressed.

55
00:03:00.690 --> 00:03:05.010
To be able to look and kind of pay attention to the calf,

56
00:03:05.010 --> 00:03:08.070
because the calf is, a lot of times what you'll see first

57
00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:09.633
or earliest in this.

58
00:03:11.070 --> 00:03:15.000
You know, now with with new developments,

59
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.670
prognosis has gotten better,

60
00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:20.250
but it's still too soon to say it's great.

61
00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:24.730
Five years ago, you were lucky to make it to your twenties

62
00:03:26.580 --> 00:03:28.200
with this disease.

63
00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:31.590
So something to pay attention to.

64
00:03:31.590 --> 00:03:34.290
Erb's palsy, brachial plexus.

65
00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:36.510
Brachial plexopathy.

66
00:03:36.510 --> 00:03:38.430
Typically, remember they won't be able

67
00:03:38.430 --> 00:03:39.600
to move their shoulder.

68
00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:42.990
We think of this oftentimes in shoulder dystocia

69
00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:45.900
during birth, which is where we will see it

70
00:03:45.900 --> 00:03:47.103
most of the time.

71
00:03:49.050 --> 00:03:52.020
The infants mostly don't move their shoulder,

72
00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:53.973
but they can move their fingers.

73
00:03:54.810 --> 00:03:57.855
And we want to be able to reassure them,

74
00:03:57.855 --> 00:04:01.500
if we think it's a stretch injury

75
00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:04.830
because they have some movement in motion intact,

76
00:04:04.830 --> 00:04:07.260
then it's really teaching the parents

77
00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:09.030
how to manage physical therapy

78
00:04:09.030 --> 00:04:12.600
and do physical therapy with their infant every day.

79
00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:14.400
Here your congenital hand deformity.

80
00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:19.400
So syndactyly is the most common congenital hand deformity.

81
00:04:20.370 --> 00:04:23.160
Can be simple or complex.

82
00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:25.680
That's clinical, that would not be on the exam,

83
00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:28.470
but the syndactyly would be.

84
00:04:28.470 --> 00:04:31.860
Polydactyly, you know, that's the extra digits.

85
00:04:31.860 --> 00:04:35.460
The ones we ligate is if I have an ulnar,

86
00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:39.090
an extra ulnar digit, then I ligate it.

87
00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:41.715
But if I have an extra middle digit, I don't.

88
00:04:41.715 --> 00:04:44.193
That's operative care for those.

89
00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:47.730
Developmental dysplasia of the hip

90
00:04:47.730 --> 00:04:49.110
and Dr. Bestie will talk

91
00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:52.230
a little bit more about this with you,

92
00:04:52.230 --> 00:04:56.040
but just to remind you, left hip is most common,

93
00:04:56.040 --> 00:04:59.203
females, first born, breach position,

94
00:04:59.203 --> 00:05:03.360
family history, and then any oligohydramnios.

95
00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:07.860
So all these are risk factors for developmental dysplasia.

96
00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:09.630
They're probably not gonna ask you

97
00:05:09.630 --> 00:05:12.390
about Ortolani's and Barlow's maneuvers.

98
00:05:12.390 --> 00:05:15.480
We use ultrasound now to make the diagnosis

99
00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:17.723
and then follow these kids.

100
00:05:17.723 --> 00:05:21.210
The Pavlik harness is what you want to utilize

101
00:05:21.210 --> 00:05:22.650
in the first six months of life.

102
00:05:22.650 --> 00:05:24.930
After that, you're gonna spike a cast them

103
00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:28.293
because now they're sitting and getting ready to crawl.

104
00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:31.083
Okay, so our first question,

105
00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:33.480
which of the following statements is true

106
00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:35.430
regarding bone tumors

107
00:05:35.430 --> 00:05:38.433
in the pediatric and adolescent population?

108
00:05:45.060 --> 00:05:48.870
Okay, D is the correct answer,

109
00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:50.796
and we're gonna go over these, okay?

110
00:05:50.796 --> 00:05:53.370
These are things that I do want you to know.

111
00:05:53.370 --> 00:05:57.750
Osteosarcoma is the most common malignant bone tumor

112
00:05:57.750 --> 00:06:00.262
in the adolescent pediatric population.

113
00:06:00.262 --> 00:06:02.880
These are gonna be incidental findings.

114
00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:06.840
You're gonna find it because the parent brings in the child

115
00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:08.550
because they're having knee pain

116
00:06:08.550 --> 00:06:11.190
or ankle pain or shoulder pain

117
00:06:11.190 --> 00:06:13.410
and they don't have a good explanation for it.

118
00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:15.390
There was no injury.

119
00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:17.940
And you're gonna find an abnormal exam

120
00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:21.210
typically by the time they bring them in, perhaps not.

121
00:06:21.210 --> 00:06:23.730
You'll get a radiograph that'll lead you down the road

122
00:06:23.730 --> 00:06:27.840
of further imaging, and then ultimately biopsy.

123
00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:30.750
Ewing's sarcoma, the second most common,

124
00:06:30.750 --> 00:06:33.360
not the most common.

125
00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:37.440
Benign bone tumors, nonossifying fibromas.

126
00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:40.560
These are benign. They're typically incidental findings.

127
00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:43.140
You're getting a radiograph for some other reason.

128
00:06:43.140 --> 00:06:45.960
And you see these typically in the distal femur

129
00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:49.950
or distal tibia is where we most often will see them.

130
00:06:49.950 --> 00:06:53.610
They tend to resolve with skeletal maturity.

131
00:06:53.610 --> 00:06:55.770
Most of them are marginal.

132
00:06:55.770 --> 00:06:57.450
They're around the cortex,

133
00:06:57.450 --> 00:07:01.170
not necessarily intramedullary completely,

134
00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:02.820
and they have sclerotic margins.

135
00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:05.340
We'll talk about that. I'll show you a radiograph.

136
00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:09.030
And then osteochondroma's are outgrowths of the bone

137
00:07:09.030 --> 00:07:11.700
and they cause most of their pain and problems

138
00:07:11.700 --> 00:07:14.460
because of soft tissue impingement.

139
00:07:14.460 --> 00:07:17.250
Occasionally, well, I wouldn't say,

140
00:07:17.250 --> 00:07:18.720
I would say early on

141
00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:23.340
when you are considering an osteochondroma

142
00:07:23.340 --> 00:07:26.010
you're gonna probably want to do some additional testing

143
00:07:26.010 --> 00:07:28.012
and you may want to get a biopsy

144
00:07:28.012 --> 00:07:30.450
because sometimes they're unclear.

145
00:07:30.450 --> 00:07:34.260
It'll depend on what the testing shows.

146
00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:37.524
But here on the left side, you see the NOF,

147
00:07:37.524 --> 00:07:39.600
the nonossifying fibroma.

148
00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:42.960
So it's marginal, it's near the cortex,

149
00:07:42.960 --> 00:07:44.970
it has sclerotic margins.

150
00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:46.830
That's typically what we see.

151
00:07:46.830 --> 00:07:49.595
And over time, there's no reason to follow this.

152
00:07:49.595 --> 00:07:53.850
I mean, it's gonna involute

153
00:07:53.850 --> 00:07:56.370
and it's gonna calcify over time.

154
00:07:56.370 --> 00:07:59.280
So there's no reason that you have to follow this,

155
00:07:59.280 --> 00:08:03.710
but just know we make the diagnosis based on the radiograph.

156
00:08:05.310 --> 00:08:10.310
And then on the right is what an osteochondroma looks like.

157
00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:13.620
And so these have the potential.

158
00:08:13.620 --> 00:08:15.450
Typically we'll get an MRI.

159
00:08:15.450 --> 00:08:17.550
Sometimes we'll get a bone scan as well

160
00:08:17.550 --> 00:08:18.570
that goes along with it.

161
00:08:18.570 --> 00:08:21.030
We put those together to try and decide,

162
00:08:21.030 --> 00:08:25.380
do we think this has some kind of question of a neoplasm

163
00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:27.240
that it needs to be biopsied.

164
00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:30.147
If not, then it's an osteochondroma

165
00:08:30.147 --> 00:08:32.070
and the diagnosis is made.

166
00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:35.460
But you see how they can cause soft tissue problems

167
00:08:35.460 --> 00:08:37.470
because they're sort of sticking out

168
00:08:37.470 --> 00:08:39.753
in areas that we don't want them.

169
00:08:41.010 --> 00:08:42.840
Okay, our next question.

170
00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:44.820
A 6-year-old female is brought to your office

171
00:08:44.820 --> 00:08:45.690
for evaluation.

172
00:08:45.690 --> 00:08:48.090
She was born at 39 and three seven weeks

173
00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:52.650
by normal spontaneous vaginal delivery without complication.

174
00:08:52.650 --> 00:08:56.460
She's met all of her orthopedic developmental milestones.

175
00:08:56.460 --> 00:08:59.100
Her mother notes, she's been more clumsy at recess,

176
00:08:59.100 --> 00:09:01.440
occasionally falling when running.

177
00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:04.014
On exam, you note that her patellae point forward

178
00:09:04.014 --> 00:09:06.420
or point inward, I'm sorry,

179
00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:08.670
and her feet point inward

180
00:09:08.670 --> 00:09:12.540
and there is no joint or limb tenderness or swelling.

181
00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:15.273
Her neurological exam is normal.

182
00:09:17.370 --> 00:09:20.523
So what is the most likely diagnosis?

183
00:09:26.040 --> 00:09:30.964
Okay, femoral anteversion is the correct answer,

184
00:09:30.964 --> 00:09:35.130
but the other half of you chose internal tibial torsion.

185
00:09:35.130 --> 00:09:38.943
So we'll find out why you chose that, okay.

186
00:09:40.020 --> 00:09:41.250
So when we look at this,

187
00:09:41.250 --> 00:09:44.010
we really have three causes of intoeing.

188
00:09:44.010 --> 00:09:47.280
The first is metatarsus adductus.

189
00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:49.080
Most of these are mild,

190
00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:52.980
most of them resolved by one to two years of age.

191
00:09:52.980 --> 00:09:54.660
There's nothing that we do for them

192
00:09:54.660 --> 00:09:57.579
short of just making the diagnosis.

193
00:09:57.579 --> 00:10:00.330
Know that this is the most common

194
00:10:00.330 --> 00:10:05.330
congenital foot abnormality, metatarsus adductus.

195
00:10:05.760 --> 00:10:07.770
Second is internal tibial torsion.

196
00:10:07.770 --> 00:10:09.510
And half of you probably chose this

197
00:10:09.510 --> 00:10:14.510
because this is the most common cause of intoeing overall.

198
00:10:15.090 --> 00:10:16.680
What do they like to ask you?

199
00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:18.570
They like to ask you questions about,

200
00:10:18.570 --> 00:10:20.130
and parents like to ask this,

201
00:10:20.130 --> 00:10:21.750
maybe physical therapy would help,

202
00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:26.750
or so and so wore a special orthotic shoes.

203
00:10:27.030 --> 00:10:29.610
Or you know, what else can we do?

204
00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:31.320
Is there a brace we can utilize?

205
00:10:31.320 --> 00:10:33.570
The answer is no, no, no and no.

206
00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:35.580
Just let them grow up with this,

207
00:10:35.580 --> 00:10:38.520
because again, most cases are mild

208
00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:42.840
and you're going to not make a decision about surgery

209
00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:47.403
until somewhere between eight and 11 years of age.

210
00:10:49.590 --> 00:10:54.360
And then our third cause of intoeing is femoral anteversion.

211
00:10:54.360 --> 00:10:58.860
So in femoral anteversion, the patellae will point inward

212
00:10:58.860 --> 00:11:02.340
when you quickly look at them where you watch their gait,

213
00:11:02.340 --> 00:11:05.643
and their toes also point inward.

214
00:11:06.480 --> 00:11:08.451
Whereas with internal tibial torsion,

215
00:11:08.451 --> 00:11:10.530
the patellae point straightforward

216
00:11:10.530 --> 00:11:12.420
and the toes point inward.

217
00:11:12.420 --> 00:11:16.050
So you can oftentimes get a very quick assessment

218
00:11:16.050 --> 00:11:18.570
simply by watching them walk.

219
00:11:18.570 --> 00:11:21.600
That will become exaggerated when you actually

220
00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:23.940
have them run down the hall toward you.

221
00:11:23.940 --> 00:11:27.034
Again, they gotta be in shorts, you know,

222
00:11:27.034 --> 00:11:30.243
or whatever so that you can see the lower extremity.

223
00:11:31.890 --> 00:11:33.240
Okay, next question.

224
00:11:33.240 --> 00:11:36.240
A 15-year-old male is brought to your office

225
00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:38.220
for evaluation of a new limp.

226
00:11:38.220 --> 00:11:40.440
He plays football as an offensive lineman

227
00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:43.440
and noted onset after practice three days ago.

228
00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:47.400
He has not been ill and had no recent immunizations.

229
00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:50.520
His examination demonstrates that he's afebrile.

230
00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:55.520
His pulse is 74, his height 72 inches, weight is 200 pounds.

231
00:11:56.640 --> 00:11:58.470
He has an antalgic gait

232
00:11:58.470 --> 00:12:01.890
and limited and painful range of motion in the left hip.

233
00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:04.893
What is your presumptive diagnosis?

234
00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:12.690
Good. And most of you got it.

235
00:12:12.690 --> 00:12:15.690
Slip capital femoral epiphysis.

236
00:12:15.690 --> 00:12:18.870
So remember with the finger,

237
00:12:18.870 --> 00:12:21.390
we asked a couple questions back to back.

238
00:12:21.390 --> 00:12:22.890
We are doing it with the hip.

239
00:12:22.890 --> 00:12:26.610
The board loves hand questions.

240
00:12:26.610 --> 00:12:30.660
The board loves pediatric hip questions.

241
00:12:30.660 --> 00:12:33.720
You could get, when I last took my boards,

242
00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:38.580
I think they had five or six pediatric hip questions on it.

243
00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:41.100
So we're not talking one or two,

244
00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:44.370
we're talking sort of series of questions.

245
00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:48.360
Okay, so this is now a 7-year-old

246
00:12:48.360 --> 00:12:49.860
brought to the emergency department

247
00:12:49.860 --> 00:12:52.350
with right hip pain and a new limp.

248
00:12:52.350 --> 00:12:55.170
Onset has been abrupt in the last 12 hours.

249
00:12:55.170 --> 00:12:57.060
There's been no trauma or injury.

250
00:12:57.060 --> 00:13:00.690
She's otherwise well and no recent illness or immunizations.

251
00:13:00.690 --> 00:13:02.970
On exam, you know that she is,

252
00:13:02.970 --> 00:13:05.462
has a temperature of 39.2 degrees centigrade,

253
00:13:05.462 --> 00:13:09.420
normal respirations, pulse and blood pressure.

254
00:13:09.420 --> 00:13:11.130
The right hip appears normal,

255
00:13:11.130 --> 00:13:12.750
is painful with range of motion

256
00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:14.463
and she limps with ambulation.

257
00:13:15.570 --> 00:13:17.370
The hip radiographs are normal.

258
00:13:17.370 --> 00:13:19.860
Which of the following is most useful

259
00:13:19.860 --> 00:13:22.503
in determining your treatment plan?

260
00:13:28.410 --> 00:13:33.410
Good. Most of you got D being the correct answer, right?

261
00:13:36.844 --> 00:13:40.410
But my question is always, why?

262
00:13:40.410 --> 00:13:43.368
Because you knew that that was really what you wanted

263
00:13:43.368 --> 00:13:46.290
or you thought it gave you the most information.

264
00:13:46.290 --> 00:13:51.290
This is a hard question and admittedly so,

265
00:13:51.450 --> 00:13:54.820
but it's because the board likes a specific data set

266
00:13:55.680 --> 00:13:58.710
and that's sometimes the case.

267
00:13:58.710 --> 00:14:00.660
So let's look at these.

268
00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:03.270
Transient synovitis is the most common

269
00:14:03.270 --> 00:14:05.820
of these hip conditions that's gonna occur.

270
00:14:05.820 --> 00:14:08.370
That's what we're gonna see most often.

271
00:14:08.370 --> 00:14:13.320
Typically it's in that four to 11 year age range.

272
00:14:13.320 --> 00:14:16.620
If the problem with this is if they're febrile

273
00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:19.860
and a large portion of them will be febrile,

274
00:14:19.860 --> 00:14:24.860
we have to discern is this septic,

275
00:14:25.220 --> 00:14:30.220
or is this toxic synovitis or transient synovitis?

276
00:14:30.420 --> 00:14:32.250
They mean the same thing.

277
00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:37.250
Or is this a spontaneous or idiopathic

278
00:14:37.530 --> 00:14:40.950
or otherwise hip abscess,

279
00:14:40.950 --> 00:14:44.523
which also occurs in this age group but is much less common.

280
00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:47.040
Okay?

281
00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:49.800
Yes, they have painful gait as all of these do.

282
00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:52.560
They have limited and painful range of motion.

283
00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:55.500
And then we're gonna talk specifically about the data

284
00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:58.860
on which tests that we're gonna get.

285
00:14:58.860 --> 00:15:01.290
For slipped capital femoral epiphysis,

286
00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:05.070
this is my younger teenagers, if you will,

287
00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:06.570
male African Americans,

288
00:15:06.570 --> 00:15:09.330
and those who are overweight and obese

289
00:15:09.330 --> 00:15:12.210
are at highest risk for this.

290
00:15:12.210 --> 00:15:16.080
If I have an acute SCFE, as in our question,

291
00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:17.280
three days, I was fine,

292
00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:18.870
three days ago after practice,

293
00:15:18.870 --> 00:15:21.390
I noted that I started having pain.

294
00:15:21.390 --> 00:15:24.480
That would be an acute situation.

295
00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:29.480
If I have that, my risk of avascular necrosis is about 30%.

296
00:15:29.850 --> 00:15:34.110
So those individuals, I want to call my orthopedic surgeon.

297
00:15:34.110 --> 00:15:37.920
I want to say I've got, you know, a teenager here

298
00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:40.290
with an acute SCFE.

299
00:15:40.290 --> 00:15:41.520
I've got radiographs.

300
00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:43.380
You want to take a look at the radiographs

301
00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:44.520
and they're likely gonna say,

302
00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:46.350
either send them to my office now

303
00:15:46.350 --> 00:15:48.120
or admit them to the hospital.

304
00:15:48.120 --> 00:15:50.850
We'll operate tomorrow, okay?

305
00:15:50.850 --> 00:15:52.650
So you wanna move quickly on them

306
00:15:52.650 --> 00:15:55.230
to reduce their risk of vascular necrosis.

307
00:15:55.230 --> 00:15:58.710
If it's chronic, if it occurs over months,

308
00:15:58.710 --> 00:16:00.360
you know, I've had this intermittent limb

309
00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:03.090
and it kind of comes back and it gets a little bit worse,

310
00:16:03.090 --> 00:16:07.260
those, they can be managed in a less acute fashion

311
00:16:07.260 --> 00:16:11.640
because the risk of avascular necrosis is markedly less.

312
00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:15.360
Legg-calve-perthes, think of this as basically

313
00:16:15.360 --> 00:16:20.360
an avascular necrosis of the epiphysis of the forming hip,

314
00:16:24.750 --> 00:16:27.870
which is why we see it primarily in toddlers.

315
00:16:27.870 --> 00:16:31.140
If they're six years old, by the time we're diagnosing it,

316
00:16:31.140 --> 00:16:33.030
they have a poor prognosis.

317
00:16:33.030 --> 00:16:35.550
And what's the treatment for it?

318
00:16:35.550 --> 00:16:37.680
You're gonna diagnose it right in your office.

319
00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:39.840
I'll show you the radiograph.

320
00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:42.930
They're gonna come in with an intermittent limp usually.

321
00:16:42.930 --> 00:16:45.330
You might not catch it on the first radiograph

322
00:16:45.330 --> 00:16:46.740
if you think about it.

323
00:16:46.740 --> 00:16:49.590
So you may reassure the parent, send them home.

324
00:16:49.590 --> 00:16:54.590
They may come back next month saying, Tommy's limping again.

325
00:16:56.010 --> 00:16:58.435
You know, and you take a look at it.

326
00:16:58.435 --> 00:17:00.660
Or Tommy's, you know,

327
00:17:00.660 --> 00:17:05.460
rubbing his thigh all the time and limping, okay.

328
00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:07.260
You repeat the radiograph

329
00:17:07.260 --> 00:17:09.450
because you may not have seen it the first time.

330
00:17:09.450 --> 00:17:11.700
Now it's developed a little bit more.

331
00:17:11.700 --> 00:17:15.000
You're not changing the outcome or the prognosis.

332
00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:19.230
It's a process that is gonna go on, if you will.

333
00:17:19.230 --> 00:17:23.280
Okay, so here's slipped capital femoral epiphysis

334
00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:25.020
on this left hip.

335
00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:27.662
And so you can see how you've lost that contour

336
00:17:27.662 --> 00:17:30.030
on the superior surface.

337
00:17:30.030 --> 00:17:33.690
And then you see the overhang on the inferior surface.

338
00:17:33.690 --> 00:17:36.353
And this is exactly what it looks like, okay?

339
00:17:42.221 --> 00:17:46.080
You may want to know Drehmann sign.

340
00:17:46.080 --> 00:17:51.080
So as you are trying to flex the hip, and I have a SCFE,

341
00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:57.783
they're gonna move into external rotation.

342
00:17:59.940 --> 00:18:01.110
So I'm not moving,

343
00:18:01.110 --> 00:18:04.590
but as I'm trying to passively flex the hip,

344
00:18:04.590 --> 00:18:07.470
the hip is gonna do this automatically.

345
00:18:07.470 --> 00:18:11.730
I can't bring it straight up because the contours changed.

346
00:18:11.730 --> 00:18:14.433
So this is the way the hip flexes.

347
00:18:15.330 --> 00:18:16.953
That's called Drehmann sign.

348
00:18:18.259 --> 00:18:23.259
If I have a young individual, so if they're less than 10,

349
00:18:23.700 --> 00:18:26.610
then I'm gonna think about this a little bit differently.

350
00:18:26.610 --> 00:18:28.620
Your orthopedic surgeon's gonna counsel them

351
00:18:28.620 --> 00:18:31.410
probably on pinning both sides.

352
00:18:31.410 --> 00:18:36.410
So treat the affected hip, but also treat the unaffected hip

353
00:18:38.280 --> 00:18:40.980
because the risk of them having this develop

354
00:18:40.980 --> 00:18:43.680
on that side is high

355
00:18:43.680 --> 00:18:46.740
and the risk of it being acute is high.

356
00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:50.220
So that means the risk of avascular necrosis is high.

357
00:18:50.220 --> 00:18:53.953
That's a worse outcome than prophylactically treating

358
00:18:53.953 --> 00:18:56.280
that hip per se.

359
00:18:56.280 --> 00:18:58.050
And then the other consideration

360
00:18:58.050 --> 00:19:00.840
is to screen these younger kids

361
00:19:00.840 --> 00:19:03.240
if they develop it less than age 10

362
00:19:03.240 --> 00:19:07.413
for thyroid and growth hormone, okay.

363
00:19:09.540 --> 00:19:11.130
Here's legg-calve-perthes,

364
00:19:11.130 --> 00:19:13.290
and this is just exactly what it looks like.

365
00:19:13.290 --> 00:19:15.990
You see that flattening and fragmentation

366
00:19:15.990 --> 00:19:19.770
of the femoral epiphysis on the left.

367
00:19:19.770 --> 00:19:21.090
This was a 4-year-old.

368
00:19:21.090 --> 00:19:23.160
This was the second time I saw the 4-year-old.

369
00:19:23.160 --> 00:19:25.470
This was the second set of radiographs.

370
00:19:25.470 --> 00:19:27.120
The first set were about,

371
00:19:27.120 --> 00:19:31.650
I don't know, six to eight weeks earlier, looked normal.

372
00:19:31.650 --> 00:19:34.800
This was the second set because I was concerned about it

373
00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:38.790
and I counseled mom, bring him back if this happens again.

374
00:19:38.790 --> 00:19:41.763
And she did. Okay, what's the treatment?

375
00:19:45.170 --> 00:19:49.080
Referral to a pediatric orthopedist if you have that.

376
00:19:49.080 --> 00:19:51.990
If you don't refer to an orthopedist,

377
00:19:51.990 --> 00:19:54.090
and what are you gonna do in the meantime?

378
00:19:56.610 --> 00:19:58.383
What's the orthopedist gonna do?

379
00:20:01.440 --> 00:20:05.010
Gonna cast them, gonna put them in a wheelchair,

380
00:20:05.010 --> 00:20:08.193
gonna put them in some kind of fancy brace.

381
00:20:09.450 --> 00:20:12.780
Orthopedist is gonna say, okay, looks good.

382
00:20:12.780 --> 00:20:17.780
Mom or dad, limit Johnny or Susie's or whoever's activity,

383
00:20:21.210 --> 00:20:23.370
I'll see you back in a month or two months

384
00:20:23.370 --> 00:20:24.870
and we'll repeat the X-rays.

385
00:20:24.870 --> 00:20:27.750
So generally that's the treatment

386
00:20:27.750 --> 00:20:29.751
you're gonna institute, right?

387
00:20:29.751 --> 00:20:33.180
There can be surgical treatment,

388
00:20:33.180 --> 00:20:36.750
but you're saying you call your orthopedic and say,

389
00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:38.640
I have a kid that has legg-calve-perthes

390
00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:40.190
and they say, yeah, yeah, okay.

391
00:20:41.310 --> 00:20:43.290
Well don't you want to see them right away?

392
00:20:43.290 --> 00:20:48.290
Oh yeah, whenever they get on the schedule is fine with me.

393
00:20:48.330 --> 00:20:49.920
Well, what am I supposed to tell them in the meantime?

394
00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:52.173
Well tell them quit running around.

395
00:20:54.720 --> 00:20:57.510
So that's the information that you give.

396
00:20:57.510 --> 00:20:59.340
But that's essentially the treatment

397
00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:00.930
is we try and limit the activity.

398
00:21:00.930 --> 00:21:02.940
We try and limit weightbearing activity.

399
00:21:02.940 --> 00:21:04.800
We do not immobilize them,

400
00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:08.700
we do not put them in wheelchairs, nothing of the sort.

401
00:21:08.700 --> 00:21:12.420
So you just try and limit their overall activity.

402
00:21:12.420 --> 00:21:15.990
Okay, we said we were gonna come back to this.

403
00:21:15.990 --> 00:21:20.220
How do I sort this out between transient synovitis

404
00:21:20.220 --> 00:21:22.680
and a septic hip?

405
00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:25.440
Well, this is something that you wouldn't

406
00:21:25.440 --> 00:21:29.310
probably otherwise know unless you're doing this regularly.

407
00:21:29.310 --> 00:21:31.260
But this is Kochers data

408
00:21:31.260 --> 00:21:35.160
and this is something that's somewhat unique to our board.

409
00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:39.420
They like this data. They ask questions about this data.

410
00:21:39.420 --> 00:21:43.860
If I'm trying to discern the difference between

411
00:21:43.860 --> 00:21:47.160
does my patient have transient synovitis of the hip

412
00:21:47.160 --> 00:21:49.710
or do they have a septic hip?

413
00:21:49.710 --> 00:21:52.020
Then I'm gathering this data.

414
00:21:52.020 --> 00:21:53.910
What's their weight bearing status?

415
00:21:53.910 --> 00:21:55.470
What's their temperature?

416
00:21:55.470 --> 00:21:57.270
What's their white blood cell count?

417
00:21:57.270 --> 00:21:59.070
What's their sedimentation rate.

418
00:21:59.070 --> 00:22:01.410
And what's their c-reactive protein.

419
00:22:01.410 --> 00:22:05.760
I take that data and I put it together.

420
00:22:05.760 --> 00:22:10.518
And if I have more than three,

421
00:22:10.518 --> 00:22:13.740
if I have four or five that are positive,

422
00:22:13.740 --> 00:22:15.690
then I wanna ultrasound that hip

423
00:22:15.690 --> 00:22:17.580
and probably gonna aspirate it.

424
00:22:17.580 --> 00:22:20.430
The reason I don't just go straight to an ultrasound

425
00:22:20.430 --> 00:22:23.583
is most of these kids will have some joint fluid in there.

426
00:22:24.420 --> 00:22:26.910
So that doesn't really help me.

427
00:22:26.910 --> 00:22:29.400
That's why the hip hurts in the first place.

428
00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:32.610
The capsule and the synovium are reactive

429
00:22:32.610 --> 00:22:34.260
and so they produce some fluid.

430
00:22:34.260 --> 00:22:37.380
And so I have an effusion in that hip anyway.

431
00:22:37.380 --> 00:22:38.400
I'm trying to decide,

432
00:22:38.400 --> 00:22:41.400
do I need to stick a needle in it or not?

433
00:22:41.400 --> 00:22:45.930
Do I need to then start treating this child or not?

434
00:22:45.930 --> 00:22:48.540
Do I need to admit them to the hospital or not?

435
00:22:48.540 --> 00:22:52.200
So there's a whole process that's involved with this.

436
00:22:52.200 --> 00:22:54.570
But anyway, this is the data they like.

437
00:22:54.570 --> 00:22:56.820
If I have one or two that are positive

438
00:22:56.820 --> 00:22:59.580
and the rest are negative, I'm not gonna do anything.

439
00:22:59.580 --> 00:23:00.660
I'll reassure them.

440
00:23:00.660 --> 00:23:03.660
I'll probably see them back in 24 hours

441
00:23:03.660 --> 00:23:05.013
and see how they're doing.

442
00:23:07.320 --> 00:23:08.763
Okay, next question.

443
00:23:09.930 --> 00:23:12.150
A 12-year-old male was brought in for evaluation

444
00:23:12.150 --> 00:23:13.200
of his right elbow pain.

445
00:23:13.200 --> 00:23:15.750
He's a pitcher on his middle school baseball team.

446
00:23:15.750 --> 00:23:17.040
Onset was insidious,

447
00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:19.320
occurred about three weeks into the baseball season,

448
00:23:19.320 --> 00:23:22.200
is aggravated by throwing and relieved by rest.

449
00:23:22.200 --> 00:23:25.800
He's noted decreased velocity and accuracy of his pitches.

450
00:23:25.800 --> 00:23:29.280
On exam, you note tenderness at the right medial epicondyle.

451
00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:31.230
You conclude the following.

452
00:23:31.230 --> 00:23:34.350
A, this is a lateral epicondylar stress fracture.

453
00:23:34.350 --> 00:23:35.975
B, this is an apophysitis.

454
00:23:35.975 --> 00:23:37.980
C, this is golfer's elbow.

455
00:23:37.980 --> 00:23:40.053
D, this is tennis elbow.

456
00:23:45.450 --> 00:23:48.063
Okay good. This is an apophysitis.

457
00:23:49.290 --> 00:23:52.650
So you know, just like we talked about overuse injuries,

458
00:23:52.650 --> 00:23:57.480
the apophysitis are overuse injuries, if you will,

459
00:23:57.480 --> 00:24:02.190
but they just affect the pediatric population.

460
00:24:02.190 --> 00:24:07.190
Remember the apophysis is not the physis, right?

461
00:24:09.584 --> 00:24:14.584
The physis is a growth center for lengthening a bone.

462
00:24:15.780 --> 00:24:20.780
The apophysis, we call a secondary ossification center

463
00:24:20.910 --> 00:24:24.060
because it's just bone and bone uniting.

464
00:24:24.060 --> 00:24:26.372
They're just growing together, okay?

465
00:24:26.372 --> 00:24:31.372
Nothing's being elongated. They're simply fusing together.

466
00:24:32.340 --> 00:24:34.800
It's taking the site

467
00:24:34.800 --> 00:24:38.100
where a major tendon inserts on the bone

468
00:24:38.100 --> 00:24:40.710
and fusing that to the underlying bone.

469
00:24:40.710 --> 00:24:44.673
Where that fusion occurs is called the apophysis.

470
00:24:45.600 --> 00:24:48.960
So the patellar tendon, the tibial tubercle,

471
00:24:48.960 --> 00:24:51.810
I have an apophysis where the tibial tubercle

472
00:24:51.810 --> 00:24:55.170
is going to ultimately attach to the tibia.

473
00:24:55.170 --> 00:24:59.530
The achilles attaches to the calcaneal apophysis,

474
00:24:59.530 --> 00:25:03.030
which which eventually is gonna attach to

475
00:25:03.030 --> 00:25:07.680
or grow to the calcaneus so that they attach.

476
00:25:07.680 --> 00:25:10.470
That's what we refer to as the apophysis.

477
00:25:10.470 --> 00:25:13.140
So in this population, I have these,

478
00:25:13.140 --> 00:25:17.190
think of the apophysis as the weak link, all right?

479
00:25:17.190 --> 00:25:18.930
And then think about what we talked about

480
00:25:18.930 --> 00:25:20.760
in terms of overuse injury.

481
00:25:20.760 --> 00:25:25.760
I have repetitive activity that I start somewhat suddenly.

482
00:25:25.920 --> 00:25:29.310
Okay, I start a new sport, I start gym class.

483
00:25:29.310 --> 00:25:33.000
At recess, we're practicing running now or jump roping

484
00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:34.440
or whatever it might be.

485
00:25:34.440 --> 00:25:37.230
So we're doing a lot of that all at once.

486
00:25:37.230 --> 00:25:39.273
And I have limited time for recovery.

487
00:25:40.440 --> 00:25:43.660
Now in probably most of your populations,

488
00:25:43.660 --> 00:25:48.150
that means that the child is going to soccer

489
00:25:48.150 --> 00:25:50.880
on Monday and Tuesday and Thursday,

490
00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:55.880
maybe doing gymnastics on Wednesday and Friday

491
00:25:56.040 --> 00:25:59.910
and you know, maybe playing with their friends or something

492
00:25:59.910 --> 00:26:01.830
on Saturday, okay?

493
00:26:01.830 --> 00:26:04.470
Doesn't have to be the same activity,

494
00:26:04.470 --> 00:26:09.470
but it's enough of the same repetitive actions, okay?

495
00:26:10.500 --> 00:26:13.770
These are clinical diagnoses.

496
00:26:13.770 --> 00:26:18.770
Do not fall for the trick of getting imaging

497
00:26:19.950 --> 00:26:22.053
in order to make your diagnosis.

498
00:26:23.070 --> 00:26:26.793
They're clinical diagnoses. Okay?

499
00:26:28.620 --> 00:26:33.620
So this case was little league elbow pitching.

500
00:26:33.630 --> 00:26:35.970
Typically the middle school pitcher,

501
00:26:35.970 --> 00:26:40.920
anywhere from three to five weeks into the season,

502
00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:42.330
they're throwing too much.

503
00:26:42.330 --> 00:26:45.600
They start developing this medial elbow pain.

504
00:26:45.600 --> 00:26:48.930
The pitching accuracy, velocity, et cetera,

505
00:26:48.930 --> 00:26:50.430
all starts to fall off

506
00:26:50.430 --> 00:26:53.040
and they come in to tell you about that.

507
00:26:53.040 --> 00:26:54.390
And when you examine them,

508
00:26:54.390 --> 00:26:57.480
you find tenderness at the medial epicondyle

509
00:26:57.480 --> 00:27:01.350
because I have an epiphysis at that site

510
00:27:01.350 --> 00:27:05.100
for my wrist flexors, okay?

511
00:27:05.100 --> 00:27:08.010
That's the weak link in the chain.

512
00:27:08.010 --> 00:27:10.710
So what do we do with these individuals?

513
00:27:10.710 --> 00:27:13.960
In this specific case, we stop all their throwing

514
00:27:15.030 --> 00:27:17.880
for three to six weeks until all their pain resolves.

515
00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:20.940
And then we start them on a rehabilitative program.

516
00:27:20.940 --> 00:27:25.710
So with physical therapy, typically not their coaches,

517
00:27:25.710 --> 00:27:27.420
typically a physical therapist

518
00:27:27.420 --> 00:27:31.140
and they start a rehabilitative throwing program.

519
00:27:31.140 --> 00:27:33.750
That's gonna take another three to six weeks

520
00:27:33.750 --> 00:27:35.610
for them to be able to do that.

521
00:27:35.610 --> 00:27:38.670
And then they can gradually return to activity.

522
00:27:38.670 --> 00:27:41.730
You also need to know that major league baseball

523
00:27:41.730 --> 00:27:43.740
has put out some preventive measures

524
00:27:43.740 --> 00:27:45.573
and you need to know what these are.

525
00:27:47.070 --> 00:27:49.203
Four months of rest per year.

526
00:27:50.610 --> 00:27:53.133
No use of radar guns.

527
00:27:54.365 --> 00:27:59.365
And people need to avoid being pitcher and catcher.

528
00:28:00.090 --> 00:28:03.420
They can't play both positions. It's one or the other.

529
00:28:03.420 --> 00:28:06.390
They're the only two positions in baseball

530
00:28:06.390 --> 00:28:10.503
that handle the ball every single play, okay?

531
00:28:13.770 --> 00:28:17.290
But I want you to also realize that

532
00:28:19.080 --> 00:28:21.930
there's a bit of nomenclature here

533
00:28:21.930 --> 00:28:25.080
that can become a little tricky.

534
00:28:25.080 --> 00:28:28.723
Medial epicondylar apophysitis.

535
00:28:30.660 --> 00:28:33.630
And don't confuse that with little league.

536
00:28:33.630 --> 00:28:35.610
That's little league elbow.

537
00:28:35.610 --> 00:28:37.710
Don't confuse that with little league shoulder

538
00:28:37.710 --> 00:28:40.230
because they're entirely different.

539
00:28:40.230 --> 00:28:42.390
And you're gonna have to know the difference between the two

540
00:28:42.390 --> 00:28:47.250
because you'll see them as potential answers multiple times.

541
00:28:47.250 --> 00:28:49.920
So you need to know what each one is.

542
00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:54.920
Little league shoulder is a proximal humeral epiphysitis,

543
00:28:56.730 --> 00:29:00.600
not apophysitis, epiphysitis.

544
00:29:00.600 --> 00:29:02.155
So think of it as a stress fracture

545
00:29:02.155 --> 00:29:05.670
of the growth plate, right?

546
00:29:05.670 --> 00:29:07.080
So little league shoulder,

547
00:29:07.080 --> 00:29:09.480
stress fracture of the growth plate.

548
00:29:09.480 --> 00:29:14.480
Little league elbow, it's an apophysitis at the elbow

549
00:29:15.390 --> 00:29:18.600
involving two completely different structures.

550
00:29:18.600 --> 00:29:20.670
So why is that important?

551
00:29:20.670 --> 00:29:23.940
Well, if I have a stress structure of the growth plate,

552
00:29:23.940 --> 00:29:25.803
that's gonna affect growth.

553
00:29:26.670 --> 00:29:31.670
Whereas if I have an overuse injury of the apophysis,

554
00:29:32.610 --> 00:29:37.050
that's just gonna cause more pain, all right,

555
00:29:37.050 --> 00:29:39.300
but it's not gonna affect growth.

556
00:29:39.300 --> 00:29:43.590
So you need to be able to discern the difference

557
00:29:43.590 --> 00:29:45.660
between the two of these.

558
00:29:45.660 --> 00:29:47.970
Okay, question six.

559
00:29:47.970 --> 00:29:50.070
An 11-year-old male is brought to your office

560
00:29:50.070 --> 00:29:52.860
for evaluation of bilateral posterior heel pain

561
00:29:52.860 --> 00:29:54.930
that occurred for the past few months.

562
00:29:54.930 --> 00:29:57.390
He plays basketball and soccer several times a week

563
00:29:57.390 --> 00:29:58.860
and the pain begins several minutes

564
00:29:58.860 --> 00:30:00.630
into each of these activities.

565
00:30:00.630 --> 00:30:03.060
There is no pain with rest or walking.

566
00:30:03.060 --> 00:30:05.550
He denies numbness, tingling, or weakness.

567
00:30:05.550 --> 00:30:07.980
On exam, you find no swelling or tenderness

568
00:30:07.980 --> 00:30:11.160
of the heel or achilles tendon.

569
00:30:11.160 --> 00:30:13.230
Reflexes, strength and range of motion

570
00:30:13.230 --> 00:30:14.490
at the ankle are intact.

571
00:30:14.490 --> 00:30:17.400
But he does have bilateral posterior heel pain

572
00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:20.793
when you passively and fully dorsi flex the ankles.

573
00:30:21.930 --> 00:30:23.523
So the question is,

574
00:30:25.050 --> 00:30:27.843
which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?

575
00:30:30.120 --> 00:30:33.750
Plantar fasciitis, Severs disease,

576
00:30:33.750 --> 00:30:37.027
heel pad syndrome, or Achilles tendonopathy.

577
00:30:41.940 --> 00:30:43.890
Okay, good. Severs disease.

578
00:30:43.890 --> 00:30:46.290
So this is an apophysitis.

579
00:30:46.290 --> 00:30:49.050
Here's a table that you can look at,

580
00:30:49.050 --> 00:30:52.590
the ones that, for those of you who are taking the exam,

581
00:30:52.590 --> 00:30:55.290
the ones to really pay attention to are

582
00:30:55.290 --> 00:31:00.137
Osgood Schlatter's and Severs to know those.

583
00:31:00.137 --> 00:31:03.510
But the others are common ones that we run into.

584
00:31:03.510 --> 00:31:06.270
And common ones that you've probably seen

585
00:31:06.270 --> 00:31:08.013
in your office as well.

586
00:31:09.840 --> 00:31:13.290
Pelvic avulsion fractures, just to mention these,

587
00:31:13.290 --> 00:31:16.110
really common in sprinting sports,

588
00:31:16.110 --> 00:31:19.620
you know, sports that require stopping and starting.

589
00:31:19.620 --> 00:31:22.050
And you get this forceful muscle contraction

590
00:31:22.050 --> 00:31:24.840
and you just, you're pulling this bone,

591
00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:28.350
these are apophysis and you're just pulling the bone

592
00:31:28.350 --> 00:31:30.930
away from the underlying bone.

593
00:31:30.930 --> 00:31:31.980
And this is the pelvis.

594
00:31:31.980 --> 00:31:34.560
So it's anterior superior iliac spine,

595
00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:36.630
anterior inferior iliac spine.

596
00:31:36.630 --> 00:31:40.800
It could be the iliac crest and the ischial tuberosity.

597
00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:44.910
So these are all places that you can just pull the bone

598
00:31:44.910 --> 00:31:47.760
away from the other underlying bone.

599
00:31:47.760 --> 00:31:50.610
You're gonna treat these just like you would a fracture.

600
00:31:50.610 --> 00:31:52.080
It's always gonna be crutches

601
00:31:52.080 --> 00:31:54.330
'cause they're incredibly painful.

602
00:31:54.330 --> 00:31:56.640
We're not thinking about surgery,

603
00:31:56.640 --> 00:31:58.560
even though the recommendations are,

604
00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:01.380
if you have two centimeters of displacement,

605
00:32:01.380 --> 00:32:05.070
you ought to surgically fix it, I've never done that.

606
00:32:05.070 --> 00:32:07.410
I've never seen anybody do it.

607
00:32:07.410 --> 00:32:09.720
We talk about it at meetings all the time.

608
00:32:09.720 --> 00:32:14.460
Nobody's ever done it. They heal regardless.

609
00:32:14.460 --> 00:32:16.680
So you put them on crutches

610
00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:20.460
and let them weight bear as tolerated.

611
00:32:20.460 --> 00:32:23.370
In pediatric ACL injuries,

612
00:32:23.370 --> 00:32:28.370
it's important that once you diagnose a pediatric ACL tear,

613
00:32:29.970 --> 00:32:34.970
if that child has another episode of instability

614
00:32:36.480 --> 00:32:41.480
in that knee, they are causing additional damage, okay?

615
00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:48.690
So pediatric ACL injuries,

616
00:32:48.690 --> 00:32:51.960
if they have another episode of instability,

617
00:32:51.960 --> 00:32:54.242
if their knee gives out on them

618
00:32:54.242 --> 00:32:56.370
after they've ruptured the ACL,

619
00:32:56.370 --> 00:32:59.550
you need to push towards reconstruction

620
00:32:59.550 --> 00:33:03.630
because they're continuing to damage that knee.

621
00:33:03.630 --> 00:33:06.600
And you can do an ACL repair.

622
00:33:06.600 --> 00:33:07.860
You know, there was a big push

623
00:33:07.860 --> 00:33:10.470
about these physeal sparing techniques

624
00:33:10.470 --> 00:33:13.500
that were being done for ACL repair

625
00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:17.100
so that we didn't interrupt growth in individuals.

626
00:33:17.100 --> 00:33:21.300
For the most part, the biggest group that's affected

627
00:33:21.300 --> 00:33:23.670
is 12 to 16.

628
00:33:23.670 --> 00:33:26.010
It becomes a non-issue at that point in time

629
00:33:26.010 --> 00:33:28.890
because for the most part, their vertical growth is done

630
00:33:28.890 --> 00:33:32.940
and there has not been good documentation

631
00:33:32.940 --> 00:33:35.730
that it has in fact interrupted growth.

632
00:33:35.730 --> 00:33:37.983
So they go ahead and get repaired.

633
00:33:39.540 --> 00:33:43.410
Idiopathic scoliosis, I don't want you to focus much on this

634
00:33:43.410 --> 00:33:45.450
other than you know,

635
00:33:45.450 --> 00:33:48.390
to realize that there's infantile juvenile

636
00:33:48.390 --> 00:33:51.300
and adolescent idiopathic scoliosis.

637
00:33:51.300 --> 00:33:54.540
And know that for adolescent idiopathic scoliosis,

638
00:33:54.540 --> 00:33:57.720
USPSTF has changed their recommendation,

639
00:33:57.720 --> 00:34:01.140
from a recommendation to screen

640
00:34:01.140 --> 00:34:06.140
to a recommendation of insufficient evidence, okay?

641
00:34:06.210 --> 00:34:09.960
For adolescent idiopathic scoliosis.

642
00:34:09.960 --> 00:34:12.510
Okay, and our last question here.

643
00:34:12.510 --> 00:34:14.400
Pediatric obesity is associated

644
00:34:14.400 --> 00:34:16.383
with each of the following, except.

645
00:34:18.150 --> 00:34:23.150
Is it impaired mobility, an overall lower risk of fracture,

646
00:34:26.220 --> 00:34:28.533
longer fracture healing times,

647
00:34:29.430 --> 00:34:32.550
or higher risk of surgical complications

648
00:34:32.550 --> 00:34:34.323
for fracture repair.

649
00:34:40.410 --> 00:34:45.410
Okay, so yes, pediatric obesity, impaired mobility, yes.

650
00:34:47.100 --> 00:34:50.280
They have longer fracture healing times, yes.

651
00:34:50.280 --> 00:34:53.010
They're more likely to require surgical intervention

652
00:34:53.010 --> 00:34:56.520
for their fracture than those who are non-obese.

653
00:34:56.520 --> 00:35:00.570
They're more likely to end up in the ICU after surgery

654
00:35:00.570 --> 00:35:01.920
than the non-obese.

655
00:35:01.920 --> 00:35:05.190
They're more likely to have a DVT post-surgery

656
00:35:05.190 --> 00:35:06.930
than the non-obese.

657
00:35:06.930 --> 00:35:08.253
Complications.

658
00:35:09.300 --> 00:35:13.230
More likely to have low back pain, arthritis,

659
00:35:13.230 --> 00:35:16.800
SCFE, you are already aware of that, et cetera.

660
00:35:16.800 --> 00:35:20.760
So all of these are associated with obesity

661
00:35:20.760 --> 00:35:22.950
in the pediatric and adolescent population.

662
00:35:22.950 --> 00:35:24.330
And that's it. Thank you.

663
00:35:24.330 --> 00:35:26.530
<v Presenter>Thank you very much, Dr. Gary.</v>

664
00:35:27.372 --> 00:35:29.872
(soft music)

